Just to start, I would love to have you guys introduce

00:00:36.770 --> 00:00:39.210
yourselves, a little bit about yourself, what you're working

00:00:39.250 --> 00:00:39.440
on.

00:00:39.450 --> 00:00:40.590
Then we'll go from there.

00:00:40.610 --> 00:00:41.380
All right.

00:00:41.390 --> 00:00:42.520
Sounds good.

00:00:42.530 --> 00:00:43.240
Welcome, guys.

00:00:43.250 --> 00:00:44.260
Hey.

00:00:44.270 --> 00:00:44.980
There we go.

00:00:44.990 --> 00:00:45.480
There we go.

00:00:45.490 --> 00:00:46.600
Well, hi, everybody.

00:00:46.610 --> 00:00:47.520
I'm Paul Frazee.

00:00:47.530 --> 00:00:49.040
I'm the CTO at Blue Sky.

00:00:49.050 --> 00:00:53.300
I think the specific reason I'm on the panel is because

00:00:53.300 --> 00:00:56.880
back when Blue Sky was very small, I was the lead

00:00:57.120 --> 00:00:59.340
engineer on building the Blue Sky application.

00:01:00.010 --> 00:01:03.020
Which I did with Expo and React Native.

00:01:03.030 --> 00:01:05.800
And I'll just go ahead and spoiler alert.

00:01:05.810 --> 00:01:08.790
Wouldn't have been able to do it without the help of

00:01:08.790 --> 00:01:09.780
Expo and React Native.

00:01:09.970 --> 00:01:12.180
So I'm here to share that story.

00:01:12.190 --> 00:01:14.960
My name's Elim Allen.

00:01:14.970 --> 00:01:18.440
I'm the founder and CEO of StreamPlace.

00:01:18.450 --> 00:01:21.570
If you're watching this remotely right now, that's that

00:01:21.570 --> 00:01:22.300
thing.

00:01:23.130 --> 00:01:29.160
And I also, from the start, we have built Stream

00:01:29.160 --> 00:01:33.140
Place using Expo and React Native WebRTC and

00:01:33.140 --> 00:01:37.000
some other technologies that we will get into.

00:01:39.510 --> 00:01:42.590
And I'm Reid, the CTO of Skylight Social

00:01:42.590 --> 00:01:42.940
.

00:01:42.950 --> 00:01:45.340
And we built Skylight on Expo.

00:01:45.350 --> 00:01:48.140
I've been using React Native since, like, 2017.

00:01:48.150 --> 00:01:53.580
And when we thought about how to build this video app,

00:01:53.590 --> 00:01:55.190
we were like, okay, well, we're going to

00:01:55.400 --> 00:01:56.280
start with React Native.

00:01:56.990 --> 00:02:00.690
And then luckily for us, the video component itself was already

00:02:00.690 --> 00:02:02.890
a library that Expo was offering.

00:02:02.910 --> 00:02:05.830
So we were able to get, like, a working prototype

00:02:05.840 --> 00:02:10.660
in two days and kind of release it before TikTok had gotten

00:02:10.660 --> 00:02:12.320
banned last January.

00:02:12.330 --> 00:02:13.240
Cool.

00:02:13.250 --> 00:02:15.810
So, Paul, just to start with you, you mentioned

00:02:15.810 --> 00:02:17.850
, you know, Expo made a lot of stuff possible

00:02:17.850 --> 00:02:18.080
.

00:02:18.090 --> 00:02:19.940
And so I wanted to start, this is to the whole

00:02:19.940 --> 00:02:22.080
panel, but, like, what is Expo specifically made

00:02:22.180 --> 00:02:22.660
possible?

00:02:22.670 --> 00:02:24.260
What is AppRoto made possible?

00:02:24.270 --> 00:02:25.380
I guess those guys built on it.

00:02:25.390 --> 00:02:27.330
But, like, how have they kind of combined in building

00:02:27.330 --> 00:02:29.320
up Blue Sky, especially in the early days?

00:02:29.330 --> 00:02:33.830
Yeah, so should we assume that people know what Expo

00:02:33.830 --> 00:02:34.080
is?

00:02:34.090 --> 00:02:34.440
I can...

00:02:34.450 --> 00:02:34.960
Oh, yes.

00:02:34.970 --> 00:02:35.500
Okay.

00:02:35.510 --> 00:02:38.420
Maybe I'm kind of happy to give a very quick intro

00:02:38.420 --> 00:02:38.720
.

00:02:38.730 --> 00:02:40.810
Expo is a way to build cross-platform mobile

00:02:40.810 --> 00:02:41.100
apps.

00:02:41.110 --> 00:02:44.180
We're the main way of building mobile apps with JavaScript or

00:02:44.320 --> 00:02:47.020
TypeScript, and then they run on both iOS and Android

00:02:47.110 --> 00:02:47.200
.

00:02:47.210 --> 00:02:47.680
Yeah.

00:02:47.690 --> 00:02:52.760
Well, and so for us, kicking off, we had

00:02:52.760 --> 00:02:56.230
12 people, maybe, when we were first writing the Blue

00:02:56.250 --> 00:02:57.010
Sky...

00:02:57.030 --> 00:02:57.840
Actually, not even that.

00:02:57.850 --> 00:02:59.700
I think we were maybe at, like, 6 when we

00:02:59.700 --> 00:03:01.020
were first building the application.

00:03:01.030 --> 00:03:05.880
And the reality is that when you have a code base that

00:03:05.880 --> 00:03:09.840
is an application for every code base you have, it's

00:03:09.840 --> 00:03:11.440
a different product, more or less.

00:03:11.450 --> 00:03:14.350
So if you're trying to write for both, you know

00:03:14.350 --> 00:03:17.560
, free platforms, really, iOS, Android, and web

00:03:17.560 --> 00:03:20.140
, if you're building three different code bases, you basically

00:03:20.140 --> 00:03:23.100
have three different products with their own teams that are maintaining their

00:03:23.100 --> 00:03:24.940
own roadmaps, their own issue trackers, and

00:03:24.940 --> 00:03:25.540
things like that.

00:03:25.550 --> 00:03:27.870
And you're kind of just working with each other on the

00:03:27.870 --> 00:03:30.180
concepts that you're going to, you know, implement on

00:03:30.180 --> 00:03:31.400
each one of them.

00:03:31.410 --> 00:03:34.820
You see this sometimes, actually, when you switch between apps

00:03:34.820 --> 00:03:35.000
.

00:03:35.010 --> 00:03:38.060
Like, I think Twitter for a long time had a pretty

00:03:38.060 --> 00:03:38.900
different...

00:03:38.910 --> 00:03:40.560
Like, you would get into the Android one and be like

00:03:40.560 --> 00:03:42.680
, oh, it's kind of different, actually.

00:03:42.690 --> 00:03:43.380
That's interesting.

00:03:43.550 --> 00:03:44.600
Because it's a different product.

00:03:44.610 --> 00:03:45.620
It's a different team.

00:03:45.630 --> 00:03:49.520
So that was just not viable for us.

00:03:49.530 --> 00:03:51.920
It was just me doing front-end for a long time

00:03:51.920 --> 00:03:52.100
.

00:03:52.110 --> 00:03:55.330
And then as the complexity of the product continued to grow and

00:03:55.330 --> 00:03:58.480
more features came in, the challenge of the idea of having

00:03:58.480 --> 00:04:01.110
multiple code bases became even less viable, even though we were

00:04:01.110 --> 00:04:01.720
getting more help.

00:04:01.730 --> 00:04:05.160
So having one code base to target all three of the platforms

00:04:05.370 --> 00:04:09.760
using technologies that we were already familiar with has certainly helped as

00:04:09.760 --> 00:04:10.060
well.

00:04:10.250 --> 00:04:14.140
TypeScript and React and, you know, essentially CSS,

00:04:14.320 --> 00:04:19.000
kind of a CSS variant, really helped us hit the timelines

00:04:19.000 --> 00:04:19.420
that we needed.

00:04:19.430 --> 00:04:21.060
And it's no joke.

00:04:21.070 --> 00:04:25.680
You can't ship just iOS or just web or just Android

00:04:25.680 --> 00:04:25.900
.

00:04:25.910 --> 00:04:28.880
It's very, very limiting to do that.

00:04:28.890 --> 00:04:31.560
And people expect to have the platform be available in all three

00:04:31.560 --> 00:04:31.820
places.

00:04:31.950 --> 00:04:35.090
So I don't think we would have been able to accomplish

00:04:35.200 --> 00:04:37.470
the rollout that we needed to do and hit our business

00:04:37.470 --> 00:04:39.440
objectives if we weren't using Expo and React Native.

00:04:40.250 --> 00:04:40.440
Yeah.

00:04:40.450 --> 00:04:42.570
And so, Eli, same question to you, although I

00:04:42.570 --> 00:04:45.040
'm curious also for Streamplay Switches obviously dealing with video

00:04:45.040 --> 00:04:47.410
, like how is that working with Expo and kind of

00:04:47.410 --> 00:04:48.930
shipping to multiple platforms?

00:04:48.970 --> 00:04:49.940
Yeah, yeah.

00:04:49.950 --> 00:04:51.670
I mean, the first part of the answer is the same

00:04:51.770 --> 00:04:52.180
, right?

00:04:52.190 --> 00:04:56.720
Like, so building any kind of Twitch competitor, we very

00:04:56.720 --> 00:04:59.520
much needed an iOS, an Android app, and a website

00:04:59.520 --> 00:05:00.880
as quickly as humanly possible.

00:05:00.890 --> 00:05:03.040
And I just don't think there's...

00:05:03.050 --> 00:05:06.160
Maybe there's other frameworks that would argue with it, but

00:05:06.160 --> 00:05:08.280
I think Expo's the most credible way to try and

00:05:08.280 --> 00:05:10.000
do all of those things.

00:05:10.010 --> 00:05:13.690
The other piece for us, you know, part of Stream

00:05:13.690 --> 00:05:18.020
play's strategy as a company is that live video infrastructure and

00:05:18.020 --> 00:05:21.060
software is very, very difficult, one of the harder things

00:05:21.120 --> 00:05:22.540
you can do in technology.

00:05:22.550 --> 00:05:26.010
And a lot of the other teams in the atmosphere aren't

00:05:26.010 --> 00:05:27.740
very excited about taking that on.

00:05:27.750 --> 00:05:30.700
So from the beginning, we've really, really wanted to

00:05:30.880 --> 00:05:31.420
...

00:05:31.430 --> 00:05:33.980
As much of our code as possible needs to live in libraries

00:05:34.010 --> 00:05:37.920
that are accessible to other applications that they can access.

00:05:37.930 --> 00:05:41.160
And so that eventually means...

00:05:41.170 --> 00:05:44.220
Unfortunately, because Expo is not the only framework in the

00:05:44.320 --> 00:05:46.480
world, that does eventually mean we need to...

00:05:46.490 --> 00:05:49.170
And we have, in various stages of development, we have

00:05:49.170 --> 00:05:51.940
sort of like React Native slash web library.

00:05:51.950 --> 00:05:52.820
That's the main one.

00:05:52.830 --> 00:05:54.680
And then we've got like a Flutter library in development

00:05:54.680 --> 00:05:54.790
.

00:05:54.810 --> 00:05:57.100
We've got a native Swift OS library in development.

00:05:57.110 --> 00:05:59.540
We'll probably do something for Android at some point.

00:05:59.550 --> 00:06:04.600
But in terms of getting the biggest slice of the pie that

00:06:04.600 --> 00:06:09.260
we could as quickly as possible, building that with Expo

00:06:09.260 --> 00:06:12.630
and React Native and building that library made a lot of sense

00:06:12.630 --> 00:06:12.800
.

00:06:12.810 --> 00:06:15.040
Unique challenges of dealing with video.

00:06:15.050 --> 00:06:20.380
I would say that for us in particular, if you're

00:06:20.430 --> 00:06:23.690
watching the live stream now and it's working, which it

00:06:23.690 --> 00:06:30.080
seems to mostly be doing so, I attribute that mostly to

00:06:30.080 --> 00:06:32.010
WebRTC playback.

00:06:32.030 --> 00:06:33.660
That's the technology we're built on.

00:06:33.790 --> 00:06:36.420
It's the same technology that's used to power Google Meet

00:06:36.420 --> 00:06:36.420
.

00:06:36.430 --> 00:06:40.340
And if you've had a conversation in a web browser with

00:06:40.340 --> 00:06:42.640
somebody who is built on WebRTC, it's very

00:06:42.670 --> 00:06:45.360
good at, for example, if something goes wrong, reco

00:06:45.360 --> 00:06:47.750
vers because it's trying to play back the video as quickly

00:06:47.750 --> 00:06:48.260
as possible.

00:06:48.270 --> 00:06:50.060
That's been a pain.

00:06:51.110 --> 00:06:54.620
Even with as much help as we can get from the frameworks

00:06:54.680 --> 00:06:58.870
and stuff, we've had to get something like picture-

00:06:58.870 --> 00:07:00.080
in-picture playback working.

00:07:00.090 --> 00:07:02.550
So when you navigate out of the app, you still have

00:07:02.550 --> 00:07:03.540
it up there in the corner.

00:07:03.550 --> 00:07:06.130
We needed to use forked versions of different WebRTC

00:07:06.440 --> 00:07:09.530
libraries, do our own native builds, building all of this

00:07:09.530 --> 00:07:12.850
in an open source way that theoretically other people could build.

00:07:13.060 --> 00:07:15.660
So that means something we don't use from Expo is

00:07:15.660 --> 00:07:17.150
like the, I'm blanking on the name, the

00:07:17.150 --> 00:07:18.000
like cloud build.

00:07:18.010 --> 00:07:19.460
Yes, yeah.

00:07:19.470 --> 00:07:21.910
You know, because we need to be able to like build

00:07:21.910 --> 00:07:23.960
all of everything ourselves in a Docker container.

00:07:23.970 --> 00:07:26.440
So yeah, yeah.

00:07:26.450 --> 00:07:28.080
I would say like once we got it all wired up,

00:07:28.090 --> 00:07:30.830
it worked pretty well, but definitely like the build process was

00:07:30.830 --> 00:07:31.440
a big challenge.

00:07:31.450 --> 00:07:32.040
Yeah.

00:07:32.050 --> 00:07:34.440
And then Reid, you're also dealing with video in a

00:07:34.440 --> 00:07:35.860
kind of different format.

00:07:35.860 --> 00:07:38.170
So I'm curious how you've dealt with that in similar

00:07:38.170 --> 00:07:39.060
and different ways.

00:07:39.060 --> 00:07:42.000
Yeah, I'm lucky that, I think it wasn't

00:07:42.000 --> 00:07:44.890
that long before that you guys released a new Expo video

00:07:44.970 --> 00:07:45.380
package.

00:07:45.390 --> 00:07:48.560
And that helped me out a lot, obviously.

00:07:48.570 --> 00:07:51.730
Because it did allow me to start with like Expo Go

00:07:51.730 --> 00:07:51.920
.

00:07:51.930 --> 00:07:56.210
And like you're able to build these native modules in Ex

00:07:56.210 --> 00:07:56.320
po.

00:07:56.470 --> 00:07:59.140
It's kind of the most important part of it that you

00:07:59.140 --> 00:08:03.440
can go to the native side instead of the JavaScript side whenever

00:08:03.440 --> 00:08:04.460
you actually need it.

00:08:04.470 --> 00:08:07.080
So you're kind of never limited on what you can do

00:08:07.080 --> 00:08:07.230
.

00:08:07.310 --> 00:08:10.960
But Expo Go is kind of like the preset group of

00:08:11.260 --> 00:08:11.660
modules.

00:08:11.670 --> 00:08:15.440
And it just allowed us to focus on the things that like

00:08:15.440 --> 00:08:16.620
the users were caring about.

00:08:16.630 --> 00:08:20.600
Because we kind of immediately had a lot of people who were

00:08:20.600 --> 00:08:23.440
like interested in using our app or using our app.

00:08:23.450 --> 00:08:27.160
We had about 150,000 users in the first three months

00:08:27.160 --> 00:08:27.320
.

00:08:27.330 --> 00:08:32.240
And so there wasn't a lot of time to work on

00:08:32.240 --> 00:08:36.170
anything except for things that the users were actively like in our

00:08:36.170 --> 00:08:37.060
comments about.

00:08:38.070 --> 00:08:41.460
And because of Expo is basically like we just got to

00:08:41.600 --> 00:08:43.360
work on like those specific behaviors.

00:08:43.370 --> 00:08:46.730
Somebody would report a bug and because we could do over-

00:08:46.730 --> 00:08:49.650
the-air updates which are like JavaScript-only updates we

00:08:49.650 --> 00:08:53.000
could fix it like immediately and then comment back and then just

00:08:53.000 --> 00:08:54.990
move on to the next thing and just do that over and

00:08:54.990 --> 00:08:56.040
over and over again.

00:08:56.050 --> 00:08:59.760
Versus if it was a Swift app we would have had

00:08:59.760 --> 00:09:03.460
to go through a whole App Store deployment of several days before

00:09:03.460 --> 00:09:04.480
they ever got feedback.

00:09:04.650 --> 00:09:07.350
And they would have just given up on us basically in those

00:09:07.350 --> 00:09:08.320
three days.

00:09:08.330 --> 00:09:11.140
So yeah, that's been my experience.

00:09:11.150 --> 00:09:11.780
That makes sense.

00:09:11.790 --> 00:09:14.440
And then so Paul, I'm curious, you mentioned earlier

00:09:14.450 --> 00:09:17.150
like you have to build for a bunch of different platforms and

00:09:17.150 --> 00:09:19.800
like now in the kind of mobile space it's really easy

00:09:19.800 --> 00:09:21.860
to iterate on web and kind of before Expo there wasn

00:09:21.860 --> 00:09:23.220
't an easy way to iterate on mobile.

00:09:23.230 --> 00:09:25.600
But I'm curious why you even target mobile in the first

00:09:25.600 --> 00:09:25.900
place?

00:09:25.910 --> 00:09:28.270
Like why is mobile kind of important to Blue Sky as a

00:09:28.600 --> 00:09:29.090
platform?

00:09:29.110 --> 00:09:36.060
Well, the web mobile experience in a web browser is you

00:09:36.060 --> 00:09:40.220
know, pretty good but there's a lot of interaction patterns

00:09:40.230 --> 00:09:41.760
that you just can't accomplish.

00:09:41.770 --> 00:09:48.040
One hopes that PWAs will someday yeah, yeah.

00:09:48.050 --> 00:09:51.260
It seems to get jammed up and it seems to be

00:09:51.260 --> 00:09:54.000
some kind of politics between Apple, I think, and Google

00:09:54.000 --> 00:09:54.000
.

00:09:54.010 --> 00:09:56.140
Like Google really wants it because they're sold on web tech

00:09:56.220 --> 00:09:56.600
, right?

00:09:56.650 --> 00:09:58.380
So I think it's Apple that's kind of jamming

00:09:58.380 --> 00:09:58.640
it up.

00:09:58.650 --> 00:10:05.140
But the gestural interfaces are very much the expectation with mobile

00:10:05.150 --> 00:10:09.210
and I'm doing a mobile web application right now and I

00:10:09.210 --> 00:10:11.880
had to stop and go I can only tap.

00:10:11.890 --> 00:10:14.260
How do I design this?

00:10:14.270 --> 00:10:16.580
This is very interesting.

00:10:16.590 --> 00:10:18.270
I found some stuff, you know, but it's a

00:10:18.270 --> 00:10:18.760
little weird.

00:10:18.770 --> 00:10:20.950
I also can't do vibrations so there's no haptic

00:10:20.970 --> 00:10:23.840
feedback which is the worst when you press on a button and

00:10:23.840 --> 00:10:25.380
it doesn't give you a little oh gosh.

00:10:25.530 --> 00:10:28.070
So like you get a little bit crippled whenever because the

00:10:28.070 --> 00:10:30.760
web is they've Apple has been pretty opinionated about like

00:10:30.760 --> 00:10:32.740
the web should be for web documents essentially it's just not

00:10:32.740 --> 00:10:36.150
their applications runtime and so you've got to go native for

00:10:36.150 --> 00:10:38.810
that reason that's reason number one is the usability of the

00:10:38.920 --> 00:10:40.850
application and reason number two is that people look inside of the

00:10:40.850 --> 00:10:42.500
app store to find the apps.

00:10:42.510 --> 00:10:43.860
That's just how it works.

00:10:43.870 --> 00:10:47.210
If you're not there then you don't exist and I

00:10:47.630 --> 00:10:48.880
think that's pretty much it.

00:10:48.890 --> 00:10:51.560
You want to have a good experience people aren't going to

00:10:51.560 --> 00:10:52.260
accept less.

00:10:52.270 --> 00:10:54.260
There are still some people I mean the only people that are

00:10:54.260 --> 00:10:56.840
really hardcore on the web are the big real big nerds

00:10:56.850 --> 00:10:59.100
so you kind of have to meet people where they're at

00:10:59.110 --> 00:11:00.300
and that's native.

00:11:00.380 --> 00:11:04.180
Yeah and so then same question for you like why is native

00:11:04.190 --> 00:11:06.860
kind of mobile apps why is that important for a stream place

00:11:06.860 --> 00:11:07.000
?

00:11:07.430 --> 00:11:10.160
Yeah I would say it's just sort of table stakes to

00:11:10.160 --> 00:11:14.420
be taken seriously in terms of releasing something and the other piece

00:11:14.450 --> 00:11:18.860
